"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":600},{"id":1171006,"guid":"253CE730A9C211EBA6716B4AA988B374","previous_id":1171004,"previous_guid":"252E6840A9C211EBA6716B4AA988B374","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"74456DCB9C6C4C0C8A232B202F451F37","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Day 2"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"652DE90B6D50476595AC4549BF5A18BA","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Pre-amplify embryos with 1mL of pre-equilibrated amplification buffer for 30min at room temperature.<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:center\"><span>Make sure to pre-equilibrate amplification buffer to <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">room temperature<\/span><span> before use.<\/span><\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:center\"><\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">                1 \u00d7 30min    Amplification Buffer <\/div><br\/><br\/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"8784FAF0A9C611EB9E84A31B888D0C37","order_id":2,"type_id":4,"title":"duration","source":{"duration":1800,"title":""}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":1800},{"id":1171007,"guid":"254376E0A9C211EBA6716B4AA988B374","previous_id":1171006,"previous_guid":"253CE730A9C211EBA6716B4AA988B374","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"1B2FAB8F8EF046B69D6F533B0048609D","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Day 2"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"3F41CC1E53D64EF196AE41B4A999A2BA","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\"><span>During the pre-amplification step, prepare hairpins. Mix 2\u00b5L (3\u00b5M stock) of each hairpin h1 and 2\u00b5L of each hairpin h2 in 100\u00b5L of amplification buffer at <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">95\u00b0C<\/span><span> for 90sec, then cool to room temperature in a dark drawer for 30min. <\/span><\/div><\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\"><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Troubleshooting tip: Doubling hairpin concentration can help to boost signal.<\/span><\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\"><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Note: If reusing hairpins from prior experiment, heat and cool, then skip to Step 13.<\/span><\/div><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":0,"critical":[{"id":1,"title":"Incubation","icon":"IncubationIcon"}],"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1171009,"guid":"5AF41FB0A9C211EBA6716B4AA988B374","previous_id":1171007,"previous_guid":"254376E0A9C211EBA6716B4AA988B374","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"853D067AB3C34D0693F3E7F8B1B5C33B","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Day 2"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"7013FFADFD714644B677CD123527F9C7","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Remove the pre-amplification solution and add the hairpin solution.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1171010,"guid":"5B00F0F0A9C211EBA6716B4AA988B374","previous_id":1171009,"previous_guid":"5AF41FB0A9C211EBA6716B4AA988B374","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"088C268246E24869AB27CDC33916E3BE","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Day 2"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"B0AFAEEAF6164FAD82B862EC7AAE9BEC","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Incubate the embryos overnight (2\u201316h) in the <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">dark<\/span><span> at<\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\"> room temperature<\/span><span>. <\/span><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":0,"critical":[{"id":40,"title":"Overnight Step","icon":"Overnight"}],"critical_id":null,"duration":57600},{"id":1171012,"guid":"8760CDF0A9C211EBA6716B4AA988B374","previous_id":1171010,"previous_guid":"5B00F0F0A9C211EBA6716B4AA988B374","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"01465A123C134EABBF3AEE39817FAFA3","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Day 3"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"A3F27E79F734465483FB9603462D9D71","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>SAVE HAIRPIN MIXTURE. Can be reused multiple times. Save used hairpin mixtures at <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">-20\u00b0C<\/span><span>.Remove excess hairpins by washing with 1mL of 5X SSCT at room temperature: <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">                1 \u00d7 5min    5X SSCT <\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\">                1 \u00d7 5min    5X SSCT <\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\">                1 \u00d7 30min    5X SSCT <\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\">                1 \u00d7 30min    5X SSCT <\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\">                1 \u00d7 5min    5X SSCT <\/div><br\/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"C95EE3F0A9C611EB9E84A31B888D0C37","order_id":2,"type_id":4,"title":"duration","source":{"duration":300,"title":""}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"CFBBA567A9C611EBAE7D0A58A9FEAC02","order_id":3,"type_id":4,"title":"duration","source":{"duration":300,"title":""}},{"id":1054727,"guid":"D9173E50A9C611EB9E84A31B888D0C37","order_id":4,"type_id":4,"title":"duration","source":{"duration":1800,"title":""}},{"id":1054728,"guid":"E0BBF3DCA9C611EBAE7D0A58A9FEAC02","order_id":5,"type_id":4,"title":"duration","source":{"duration":1800,"title":""}},{"id":1054729,"guid":"E9C48B22A9C611EBAE7D0A58A9FEAC02","order_id":6,"type_id":4,"title":"duration","source":{"duration":300,"title":""}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#84CE84","section_duration":4500,"critical":[{"id":12,"title":"Critical step","icon":"CriticalIcon"}],"critical_id":null,"duration":4500},{"id":1171014,"guid":"87731D70A9C211EBA6716B4AA988B374","previous_id":1171012,"previous_guid":"8760CDF0A9C211EBA6716B4AA988B374","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"A391C2C00DC24BBD8D4E4B9075956F1D","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Day 3"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"BBBEB3B66BFC4D2BB9E466065090A620","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Incubate embryos in 50% glycerol solution (in 1X PBS) with DAPI (skip if DAPI is not needed):<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\">                30min-1h if using 1.0\u00b5g\/mL DAPI<\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\"><span>                2 h or overnight at <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">4\u00b0C <\/span><span>if using<\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\"> <\/span><span>0.1\u00b5g\/mL DAPI<\/span><\/div><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#84CE84","section_duration":4500,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1171015,"guid":"87784D90A9C211EBA6716B4AA988B374","previous_id":1171014,"previous_guid":"87731D70A9C211EBA6716B4AA988B374","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"FE0B243D09064C898D3A7EEF64A2CA59","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Day 3"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"CA3E663CB3C84055BF4D131F5178D278","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Replace DAPI glycerol with 50%-70% glycerol (in 1X PBS) and store at <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">4\u00b0C<\/span><span>. <\/span><\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Troubleshooting tip: 1<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;font-style:italic;\">X<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\"> PBS must be at pH 7.40, deviation from this may result in rapid loss of signal.<\/span><\/div><br\/><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#84CE84","section_duration":4500,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1171101,"guid":"537286E0A9C811EB9E84A31B888D0C37","previous_id":1171015,"previous_guid":"87784D90A9C211EBA6716B4AA988B374","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"BA6520A9B94C4AC48C475A0FB12FFC88","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Notes"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"5AC3C2171F4842C28044202E7E226C69","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\">If the sample has substantial cuticle that would normally block penetration of probes (such as Artemia), we follow the sonication procedure described in Patel 1994, as indicated in Step 1.<\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\">              <\/div><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#FFED92","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1171102,"guid":"A4332260A9C811EB9E84A31B888D0C37","previous_id":1171101,"previous_guid":"537286E0A9C811EB9E84A31B888D0C37","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"9A0E26A339C04D95A7ACC65B4863AC35","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Notes"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"354009659ABE40A3962C8E213D3E909B","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">If you have problems with changing the solutions because the embryos do not settle, fold then twist a piece of Nitex mesh over a glass Pasteur pipette to make a filter, secure twisted Nitex with a ring of cut plastic transfer pipette, and use this to remove buffer without sucking up embryos.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#FFED92","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1171104,"guid":"43245FB0A9C911EB9E84A31B888D0C37","previous_id":1171102,"previous_guid":"A4332260A9C811EB9E84A31B888D0C37","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"6E8F9D8100EF4C06B77587163D88EAFA","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Notes"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"AF62E25E587B46F3AE3E5F016276716A","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">You will note that there is no ProteinaseK treatment step in this protocol. Many years ago, when working with grasshoppers (and more standard DIG-RNA probes), we found that this ProteinaseK treatment time had to be optimized for each stage of development, and led to some degradation in morphology. We modified the DIG in situ protocol to instead use a Detergent Treatment step. In adapting the HCR protocol, we have continued with the Detergent step (Step2), and left out ProteinaseK treatment. Since there is no ProteinaseK treatment, a post-fixation step is unnecessary. Indeed, in our tests, we found that a post-fixation step (after Detergent treatment) results in a lower signal to noise ratio. Finally, addition of 0.1% SDS to the hybridization buffer was tested and deemed unnecessary.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#FFED92","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1183688,"guid":"05C6FD50BB1011EB85C20FB1606AC384","previous_id":1170999,"previous_guid":"789A9131A9C111EBA6716B4AA988B374","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"1B5EECEEAC3D479F9FB096420FDDFE06","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Day 2"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"F00C951D3F5748399A5C84D1D1E7CF71","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\"><span>Pre-heat probe wash buffer to <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">37\u00b0C<\/span><span> before use, equilibrate amplification buffer to<\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\"> room temperature <\/span><span>before use, and pre-set heat block to <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">95\u00b0C<\/span><span>.<\/span><\/div><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1213773,"guid":"A078D8A0E55411EB9A1DD126B08C57A7","previous_id":1171104,"previous_guid":"43245FB0A9C911EB9E84A31B888D0C37","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"AE5C92956B4347319C23DAE91723A213","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Notes"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"BDA118F5250646188E0D3F854898B105","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">If you would like to combine in situ and antibody staining, we have had good success with starting a standard immunofluorescence staining protocol following step 15 of this protocol. <\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#FFED92","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0}],"document":"","materials":[],"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:center\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Hybridization Chain Reaction (HCR) In Situ Protocol<\/span><\/div><\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><span>This protocol largely follows the HCR v3.0 protocol for whole-mount Drosophila embryos (Choi et al. 2018) with a few adaptations that simplify the procedure and improve signal to noise ratio in our hands. Our lab has used it with good success in <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Drosophila melanogaster<\/span><span> (fruit fly) embryos and imaginal discs, <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Junonia coenia<\/span><span> (butterfly) embryos and imaginal discs, <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Antheraea polyphemus<\/span><span>, (moth) pupal wings, <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Parhyale hawaiensis<\/span><span> (amphipod crustacean) embryos, <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Tribolium castaneum <\/span><span>(beetle) embryos, <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Artemia franciscana<\/span><span> (brine shrimp) nauplii and adults, <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Acanthoscurria geniculata<\/span><span> (tarantula) embryos, <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Daphnia magna <\/span><span>(water flea) embryos, and <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Danio rerio<\/span><span> (zebrafish) embryos. For some examples, please refer to Bruce & Patel 2020 and images below.<\/span><\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Fixation:<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Dissect tissue and fix for 10-40 minutes as you would for standard in situ or antibody staining. For fixation, we generally use 3.2% paraformaldehyde mixed in 1X artificial seawater (for <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Artemia<\/span><span> and<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\"> Parhyale<\/span><span>) or 1X PBS (for <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Junonia<\/span><span>, <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Antheraea<\/span><span>, and <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Anthoscurria<\/span><span>). For <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Drosophila <\/span><span>and <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Tribolium<\/span><span>, a standard heptane\/PEM-FA fixation, with subsequent methanol devitillenization is followed (detailed protocol in Patel 1994). We routinely dehydrate the embryos\/tissue into 100% methanol after fixation and store the samples at -20\u00b0C for several years without a problem. This dehydration in methanol is not strictly necessary, but often makes the samples less prone to floating in later steps of the protocol. We no longer carry out the xylene treatment or ProteinaseK digestion steps found in other protocols.<\/span><\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Probes:<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">We have had our probes synthesized by Molecular Instruments (Los Angeles, CA. USA). They recommend starting with a minimum of 1.4kb of sequence with 20 probe sets created from this. We have had success with shorter sequences \u2013 our shortest has been 777bp with just a 9 probe set, but obviously longer is better.<\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\">We have used five different hairpin amplifier colors (Alexa 488, 514, 546, 594, and 647) available from Molecular Instruments, and all have worked well. We routinely carry out three color in situs using the combination of Alexa 488, 546, and 647. Additionally we have had success with five color labeling experiments with up to nine probes. To create clear separation of five color channels, spectral imaging and linear unmixing have been necessary.<\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\">For some species, we have had issues with autofluorescence at shorter wavelengths. In these cases we have found that the Alexa 488 hairpins have led to a poor signal to noise ratio, and favor using the longer wavelength probes (546, 594, and 647). <\/div><br\/><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dz7ibid47.jpg\" \/><\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dz7nbid47.jpg\" \/><\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dz7sbid47.jpg\" \/><\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\">References:<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><ol style = \"list-style-type: decimal;\"><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;\">Choi HMT, Schwarzkopf M, Fornace ME, Acharya A, Artavanis G, Stegmaier J, Cunha A, Pierce NA. Third-generation in situ hybridization chain reaction: multiplexed, quantitative, sensitive, versatile, robust. Development. 2018 Jun 26;145(12):dev165753. doi: 10.1242\/dev.165753. PMID: 29945988; PMCID: PMC6031405.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;\">Rehm EJ, Hannibal RL, Chaw RC, Vargas-Vila MA, Patel NH. Fixation and dissection of Parhyale hawaiensis embryos. Cold Spring Harb Protoc. 2009 Jan;2009(1):pdb.prot5127. doi: 10.1101\/pdb.prot5127. PMID: 20147022.   <\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;\">Patel, N H. \u201cImaging neuronal subsets and other cell types in whole-mount Drosophila embryos and larvae using antibody probes.\u201d Methods in cell biology vol. 44 (1994): 445-87. doi:10.1016\/s0091-679x(08)60927-9.                             <\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;\">Bruce HS, Patel NH. Knockout of crustacean leg patterning genes suggests that insect wings and body walls evolved from ancient leg segments. Nat Ecol Evol. 2020 Dec;4(12):1703-1712. doi: 10.1038\/s41559-020-01349-0. Epub 2020 Dec 1. PMID: 33262517.<\/li><\/ol><\/div><\/div>","changed_on":1626721963}